1. Review and Evaluate Existing Security Training Materials [10M]
Evaluation Framework
1. Review Criteria

Criteria	What to Assess
Content Relevance	Covers current threats (phishing, ransomware, MFA bypass, social engineering)
Engagement Level	Interactive vs. passive (videos, quizzes, gamification)
Accessibility	Available in multiple formats, languages, mobile-friendly
Frequency	Annual vs. ongoing micro-learning
Assessment	Tests knowledge retention, not just completion
Customization	Tailored to roles (IT, finance, execs, general staff)
2. Evaluation Methods

Completion Rates: % of employees finishing training

Knowledge Checks: Average quiz scores before/after

Phishing Simulation Correlation: Compare trained vs. untrained click rates

User Feedback Surveys: Ratings and qualitative comments

Content Audit: Check for outdated examples (e.g., still using "Nigerian prince" scams vs. modern AI-generated phishing)

3. Sample Evaluation Findings

Area	Finding
Content	Good coverage of basics, but lacks emerging threats like deepfake voice scams and QR code phishing (quishing)
Engagement	20-minute annual video with 70% completion; users report it's "boring and easily forgotten"
Role-Based	One-size-fits-all; no specialized content for high-risk roles
Retention	Quiz scores drop 40% within 3 months post-training
Simulation Link	No significant difference in click rates between trained and untrained users (32% vs. 35%)
Q2. Suggest Improvements Based on Feedback & Best Practices [15M]
1. Shift from Annual to Micro-Learning
Issue: Users forget content within months.
Best Practice: Deliver 5-minute monthly modules instead of one long session.
User Feedback: "I can't remember what I learned a year ago."

2. Increase Interactivity & Gamification
Issue: Low engagement with passive video content.
Best Practice: Use scenario-based simulations, leaderboards, and rewards.
User Feedback: "It feels like a checkbox exercise."

3. Role-Based Customization
Issue: Executives and finance teams face different threats.
Best Practice:

Finance: BEC (business email compromise), fake invoice recognition

IT: Privileged account protection, supply chain attacks

Execs: Spear-phishing, impersonation threats

General: Password hygiene, MFA adoption

4. Incorporate Emerging Threats
Issue: Materials lack modern attack vectors.
Best Practice: Add modules on:

Quishing (QR code phishing)

AI-generated deepfake voice/video calls

MFA fatigue attacks (push bombing)

SMS phishing (smishing)

5. Improve Reporting & Reinforcement
Issue: Low reporting rates in simulations.
Best Practice:

Implement one-click "Report Phishing" button in email clients

Send immediate positive reinforcement when users report real or simulated threats

Display real-time dashboards showing team reporting stats

6. Measure Effectiveness Continuously
Issue: Training success measured only by completion.
Best Practice: Track Key Performance Indicators (KPIs):

Phishing simulation click rate (target: <5%)

Reporting rate (target: >20% of simulated emails)

Time to report (target: within 1 hour)

Quiz score retention over 6 months

Summary Table: Proposed Improvements
Area	Current State	Proposed Improvement
Frequency	Annual 20-min video	Monthly 5-min micro-learning
Engagement	Passive viewing	Gamified scenarios + rewards
Customization	One-size-fits-all	Role-based tracks
Threat Coverage	Basic phishing	Quishing, deepfakes, MFA fatigue
Reinforcement	None	Instant feedback + report button
Metrics	Completion only	Click rate, reporting rate, retention
